The **Boyer-Moore algorithm** is one of the most efficient string searching algorithms in practice.  
It uses two heuristics to skip ahead intelligently when mismatches occur:

1. **Bad Character Rule**: If a mismatch occurs, shift the pattern so that the mismatched character in the text aligns with the last occurrence of that character in the pattern.  
2. **Good Suffix Rule**: If a suffix of the pattern matches but a mismatch occurs before it, shift the pattern to align the next possible occurrence of that suffix.

---

## Key Points
- **Best case complexity:** O(n/m) (very fast when mismatches occur often).  
- **Worst case complexity:** O(n · m) (rare, e.g., repetitive patterns).  
- **Average case:** Much faster than naive search, especially for large alphabets.

---

## Java Implementation (Bad Character Rule Only)
import java.util.*;

class BoyerMoore {
    private final int ALPHABET_SIZE = 256; // ASCII

    // Preprocess: build last occurrence table
    private int[] buildLast(String pattern) {
        int[] last = new int[ALPHABET_SIZE];
        Arrays.fill(last, -1);
        for (int i = 0; i < pattern.length(); i++) {
            last[pattern.charAt(i)] = i;
        }
        return last;
    }

    // Search function
    public int search(String text, String pattern) {
        int[] last = buildLast(pattern);
        int n = text.length();
        int m = pattern.length();
        int i = m - 1; // index in text
        int j = m - 1; // index in pattern

        while (i < n) {
            if (text.charAt(i) == pattern.charAt(j)) {
                if (j == 0) {
                    return i; // match found
                }
                i--;
                j--;
            } else {
                int lo = last[text.charAt(i)];
                i = i + m - Math.min(j, 1 + lo);
                j = m - 1;
            }
        }
        return -1; // not found
    }

    // Example usage
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BoyerMoore bm = new BoyerMoore();
        String text = "HERE IS A SIMPLE EXAMPLE";
        String pattern = "EXAMPLE";
        int index = bm.search(text, pattern);
        System.out.println("Pattern found at index: " + index);
    }
}

Example Run
Text: "HERE IS A SIMPLE EXAMPLE"
Pattern: "EXAMPLE"
Output: Pattern found at index: 17

Summary
Boyer-Moore is highly efficient for large texts and patterns.
It skips ahead instead of checking every character.
Combining Bad Character and Good Suffix rules makes it even faster.
In practice, it often outperforms KMP and Rabin-Karp for single pattern searches.

Time Complexity: Best O(n/m), Worst O(n·m).
Idea: Skip ahead using bad‑character and good‑suffix heuristics.
Often fastest in practice for large alphabets.

Summary
Naive search (indexOf): O(n·m), simple and fine for small strings.
KMP: O(n + m), avoids redundant comparisons.
Rabin-Karp: Good for multiple pattern searches, uses hashing.
Boyer-Moore: Very efficient in practice, skips ahead intelligently.
